Items.

An item is a collectible the player picks up off the ground and carries in their inventory — a health pack, a stamina drink, a key, a stash of ammo, a quest token. Each item rests on a tile, humming a quiet loop so the player can find it by ear, and is gathered by walking onto it (and pressing the interact key, unless it's set to grab automatically). Item zones, covered at the end of this topic, spawn a steady supply of items over an area.

How an item works.

An item sits on a single tile and belongs to one of three categories — health, stamina, or other — with a specific item chosen inside that category. While it's there, it plays an ambient loop on a repeating beat so the player can hear where it is. When the player reaches its tile:

If autograb is on, the item is collected the moment the player steps onto it.
If autograb is off, the player has to press the interact key while standing on it to pick it up.

On pickup the item plays a get cue, its name is spoken, it's added to the player's inventory, and it disappears from the map. From there it lives in the player's inventory until it's used. The category is how items are grouped: health and stamina items are the consumables tied to those two stats, and other covers everything else — including the keys that key-locked doors and passages look for in the player's inventory.

Item fields.

The item form takes the following:

Coordinates. An x and y (and z on 3d maps) — the tile the item rests on.

Speed. Milliseconds between plays of the ambient loop that marks the item's position, so a smaller number makes a more insistent beacon.

Category. Health, stamina, or other — which group the item belongs to.
Item. The specific pickup within the chosen category, or none for a silent, nameless marker.

Autograb when stepped on (checkbox). When checked, the item is collected on contact; when unchecked, the player must press the interact key to pick it up.

Auditioning sounds in the builder.

While the item list is focused in the form, press space to hear the get clip of the highlighted item and hold control and press L to hear its ambient loop.

Item zones.

An item zone is a rectangular area that spawns items over time while the player is inside it. Every spawn time, it drops one item of the chosen category and type at a random tile in the zone, set to grab automatically — a fountain of health, a restocking ammo cache, a supply drop the player can stand in to keep topping up.

The item zone form takes the following:

Coordinates. A minimum and maximum x and y (and a minimum and maximum z on 3d maps) — the area items spawn in, which is also the area the player must be standing in to keep the spawns coming.

Spawn time. Milliseconds between spawns while the player is inside.

Category. Health, stamina, or other.
Item. The specific item the zone spawns.

While the item list is focused in the item zone form, press space to hear the ambient loop of the highlighted item and hold control and press L to hear its get clip.

Authoring items by hand.

If you edit main.sif directly, an item is: item x y speed category item autograb. On 3d maps a z follows y: item x y z speed category item autograb. The category is the word health, stamina, or other; the item is the folder name within that category, or none; and autograb is the literal word true or false.

An item zone is: item_zone minx maxx miny maxy spawntime category item. On 3d maps a minimum and maximum z follow the y pair: item_zone minx maxx miny maxy minz maxz spawntime category item.
